<br>
If you go in with a crowd control member, ie Enchanters, (or even) Necros or bards.  Pet control is essential.<br>
1)  Required hot keys.<br>
    - pet back off<br>
    - assist keys<br>
2)  Wait until all adds are mezzed before sending pet in.<br>
    The most important thing is to ensure your pet does not<br>
    break a mez.  To make this easier, I normally<br>
    i)  Stand near the back of the group.<br>
    ii) Stand whenever I can when a pull comes in.<br>
3)  If you or your pet has been attacked by an add and your<br>
    pet is still on main assist's target.  Wait until the<br>
    add is mezzed, once the add is mezzed, have your pet<br>
    back off to clear the hate list on your pet.  This way,<br>
    when you current target dies, your pet will not <br>
    immediately go after the add.  The main melee needs<br>
    time to taunt mob so that add does not go after your<br>
    mezzer right away.<br>
<br>
Another thing to keep in mind, do not overburn.  Keep your mana up as much as possible.  Save nukes for when you have a lot of mezzed mobs or for those mobs that gate (ie shamans and wizards.)  Another reason to keep your mana up is to feed modulation rods to your mezzer or cleric when they are LOM or OOM.  (I normally give every caster a modulation rod at the zone in, when everyone is buffing.)<br>
<br>
Mind you, these tactics should be followed everytime you enter a hard dungeon. (Ie Chardok, Howling Stones)<br>
<br>
I'm sure I'm repeating things that have been posted in this message board before, but here it is again anyway. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#989dca><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub6.ezboard.com/bthemagicianstower.showLocalUserPublicProfile?login=waldenawildfyre>Waldena Wildfyre</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Master Summoner</span><br>  Posts: 256<br> <font color=#333333>(4/30/01 5:27:31 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub102.ezboard.com/fthemagicianstowerfrm23.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=39.topic&index=4>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Sebilis Tips?</span><hr size=1> The xp in seb is much better then karnors or most other places to hunt at that level.  The problem is at that level it will be very hard to find a group.  Personally I wouldnt go to seb until 53 when you get Group DS, and air pet (the pet ya should be using in most groups).  And even then it will be hard to find a group until 55 when you get CoH.  Seb is different then most other dungons you have probably faught in.  It has a seperate zone in point then zone out point (like Chardok and HS).  And when someone leaves the group and you need a replacement, you either evac to the zone, or fight your way out, pick up the new member, then head back in.  When coming to seb I recommend you are able to be online a good deal of time nonstop that day.  Can sometimes take and hour or longer to get in a group, and once you do the group will expect you to stay at least a few hours, as it is a pain to replace members.  CoH greatly reduces this problem though, which is why after you get CoH you will have a much easier time finding a group.  After getting a group Id recommend staying at least 4 hours to make the wait worth while, longer if you can.  If you do try to get a group in the low 50s, it will be doubtfull that you will get picked up by /shout low 50 mage lfg.  My suggestion is to wait at the zone in, and when there are enough people LFG, including a chanter and/or cleric, invite them and then find an open camp, call it, then wait for the remaining needed classes to show up.  Id recommend staying in Karnors until 53. My usual strategy for groups in karnors is to get on the captains and hands/wl list (and sewers if there is a sewers group), then join a Moat, CY, or zone group until im up in hands/wl or captains.  If there isnt a sewers group I also sometimes wait till there is a cleric lfg and a 53+ bard or chanter then start one. <p><center>
